  <brief_title>Randomized Trial of Alerts in Patients Demonstrating a &quot;Triple Low&quot;</brief_title>
  <official_title>A Randomized Effectiveness Trial of Early Hemodynamic Support in Patients Demonstrating a &quot;Triple Low&quot; of Mean-arterial Pressure, End-tidal Anesthetic Concentration, and Bispectral Index</official_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>The Cleveland Clinic</agency>
      <agency_class>Other</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>The Cleveland Clinic</source>
  <oversight_info>
    <has_dmc>Yes</has_dmc>
  </oversight_info>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The investigators propose to test the theory that smart alarms for the Triple Low State
      incorporated into a decision support system built into an electronic anesthesia record will
      prompt clinicians to intervene earlier in situations that would otherwise provoke little
      concern, and that the alert system will reduce 90-day mortality. Specifically, the
      investigators will test the hypothesis that providing Triple Low alerts reduces 90-day
      mortality.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
